export const story = {"seriesId":"silly-squirrels","storyId":"the-super-secure-snack-safe","storyKey":"silly-squirrels/the-super-secure-snack-safe","seriesTitle":"Silly Squirrels","seriesDescription":"A collection of fun tales about squirrel families and their adventures","title":"The Super Secure Snack Safe","author":"Team Roughdraft","description":"Papa's emergency snack stash keeps disappearing, so Nutty builds the most secure snack safe in Nutville. Soon nobody can open it, everybody gets accused, and the safe itself becomes the biggest problem in town.","ageRange":"5-9","genre":"Comedy, Mystery","tags":["comedy","mystery","snacks","invention","family","security"],"coverImage":"/covers/silly-squirrels.jpg","chapters":[{"id":1,"number":1,"title":"The Great Snack Emergency","file":"chapter-1.md","markdown":"# Chapter 1: The Great Snack Emergency\n\nPapa Nutwobble had emergency snacks.\n\nHe had rainy-day snacks, extra-rainy-day snacks, \"what if lunch is late by seven minutes\" snacks, and a mysterious tin labeled **DO NOT OPEN UNLESS THINGS GET EXTREMELY CRUNCHY**.\n\nNobody was entirely sure what \"extremely crunchy\" meant.\n\nPapa was entirely sure it meant everything.\n\nSo when he opened the tin that Tuesday morning and found it EMPTY, he made a sound so dramatic that three birds fell out of a nearby tree from sheer surprise.\n\n\"NOOOOOOOOOOO!\" Papa cried, clutching the empty tin to his fluffy chest. \"The emergency cheese crackers are gone! The backup pretzel twists are gone! The emergency emergency cinnamon acorns are GONE!\"\n\nNutty tumbled down from the breakfast branch with his notebook already open. \"A crime?\"\n\nMama Nutwobble zipped in from her morning run so fast that she accidentally ran one extra lap around the house before stopping. \"A race?\"\n\n\"Worse,\" Papa said in a grave whisper. \"A snack robbery.\"\n\nThe family stared into the empty tin.\n\nThere were crumbs inside. Lots of crumbs.\n\nNutty adjusted his detective goggles, which were really just swimming goggles with one lens missing. \"Interesting.\"\n\n\"What do you see?\" Mama asked.\n\nNutty leaned closer. \"Cracker dust. Pretzel salt. Cinnamon sparkles. Also...\" He squinted very hard. \"A suspicious amount of Papa smell.\"\n\nPapa gasped. \"Are you suggesting I stole my own snacks?\"\n\n\"I am suggesting,\" Nutty said carefully, \"that you were definitely near your snacks.\"\n\n\"I am ALWAYS near my snacks,\" Papa said. \"That proves nothing except excellent planning.\"\n\nHe turned the tin upside down hopefully. One lonely peanut bounced out.\n\nPapa stared at it. \"A witness.\"\n\nBy the time breakfast was over, the entire town had heard the news.\n\nTony the Delivery Fox arrived first, still wearing one roller skate for some reason. \"I came as soon as I heard about the snack tragedy.\"\n\nMrs. Hedgehog marched in carrying a clipboard. \"I have organized a list of possible suspects.\"\n\n\"How many suspects?\" Nutty asked.\n\n\"Currently?\" Mrs. Hedgehog checked the clipboard. \"Everyone.\"\n\nMayor Buttersworth came puffing up the hill with his ceremonial sash on backward. \"Nutville will not rest until justice is served!\"\n\n\"Preferably with dip,\" Papa muttered.\n\nGrandma Nutwobble arrived last. She took one look at the empty tin, one look at Papa, and said, \"Hmph.\"\n\nPapa straightened. \"What does 'hmph' mean?\"\n\n\"It means either you have a thief,\" Grandma said, \"or you had a midnight snack and forgot. Could go either way.\"\n\n\"I would never forget a midnight snack,\" Papa said with deep dignity.\n\nEveryone considered this.\n\n\"That,\" said Nutty, \"is actually a very good point.\"\n\nHe leaped onto a stump and snapped his notebook shut with a dramatic flap.\n\n\"Nutville does not need more suspicion,\" he declared. \"Nutville needs SCIENCE.\"\n\nMama grinned. \"My favorite kind of sentence.\"\n\n\"We need a snack container so secure, so brilliant, so impossible to crack, that no thief, squirrel, fox, hedgehog, mayor, raccoon, or sleepy family member could EVER get into it!\"\n\nTony raised a paw. \"Should the owner be able to get into it?\"\n\nNutty paused.\n\n\"Eventually,\" he said.\n\nMrs. Hedgehog nodded thoughtfully. \"Reasonable.\"\n\nPapa's eyes slowly widened. \"A super secure snack safe.\"\n\nThe words hung in the air like fireworks made of crackers.\n\nMama bounced in place. \"With locks!\"\n\n\"And alarms!\" said Nutty.\n\n\"And maybe a little snack elevator inside?\" Papa suggested.\n\n\"No elevator,\" Nutty said. \"This is security, Papa, not comfort.\"\n\n\"What about a comfort elevator?\"\n\n\"Absolutely not.\"\n\nBy noon, the whole plan had grown legs, wheels, bells, and at least one unnecessary trumpet.\n\nThey marched to the old mill workshop, where many of Nutville's best ideas and almost all of its worst ideas had been built.\n\nNutty drew a huge rectangle on the chalkboard.\n\n\"Behold!\" he announced. \"The Super Secure Snack Safe!\"\n\nHe added labels as he spoke:\n\n- Triple lock\n- Secret code dial\n- Tail-print scanner\n- Anti-sneak alarm\n- Crumb detector\n- Backup anti-sneak alarm\n- Extra backup anti-sneak alarm in case of sneaky confidence\n\nPapa raised a paw. \"Will it hold crackers, cookies, and cinnamon acorns?\"\n\nNutty added one final note in large, serious letters:\n\n**HOLDS MANY SNACKS**\n\n\"Perfect,\" Papa whispered.\n\nSoon the workshop was buzzing.\n\nMama carried in an old boiler door from the mill.\n\nTony found a heavy metal box that had once held turnips and, according to the faded label, \"possibly fireworks.\"\n\nMrs. Hedgehog contributed tiny brass locks sorted by shininess.\n\nMayor Buttersworth donated a red emergency lever that nobody had asked for but everybody agreed looked important.\n\n\"Excellent,\" the mayor said, smoothing his backward sash. \"If this contraption works, perhaps Nutville can finally store the winter acorn fund somewhere safer than my desk drawer.\"\n\nMrs. Hedgehog looked up from her clipboard. \"The drawer labeled `Definitely Not Town Acorns`?\"\n\nThe mayor coughed. \"Security through misdirection.\"\n\nGrandma placed one plain iron key on the workbench.\nThen she placed beside it the tiniest stick of dynamite anybody in Nutville had ever seen.\n\n\"What's that for?\" Nutty asked.\n\n\"In case your fancy nonsense doesn't work,\" Grandma said.\n\n\"Are we putting dynamite in the snack safe?\" Tony asked.\n\n\"Absolutely not,\" Nutty said.\n\n\"Good,\" said Tony.\n\nGrandma slipped the tiny stick back into her apron. \"Suit yourselves.\"\n\nNutty laughed the brave laugh of someone who has never yet been humbled by a machine he built twelve minutes ago.\n\n\"Oh, Grandma,\" he said. \"This safe is going to be so secure it won't NEED a plain old key.\"\n\nGrandma folded her paws.\n\n\"That's what they always say.\"\n\nBy sunset, the safe had a metal door, four locks, a turning dial, a speaking tube, and a little sign Papa painted in enormous wobbly letters:\n\n**SUPER SECURE SNACK SAFE**\n\nThen, underneath in smaller letters:\n\n**NO CRUMB-FINGERED BANDITS ALLOWED**\n\nPapa stepped back and wiped a tear from his eye. \"It's beautiful.\"\n\nNutty nodded proudly. \"Tomorrow, we install the security systems.\"\n\nMama cracked her knuckles. \"How many security systems?\"\n\nNutty smiled a smile that should have made everyone much more nervous than it did.\n\n\"All of them,\" he said.\n\nAnd somewhere, very faintly, Grandma sighed the sigh of a squirrel who could already see the future and knew it was about to be hilarious.\n","narration":null},{"id":2,"number":2,"title":"Maximum Security, Minimum Snacking","file":"chapter-2.md","markdown":"# Chapter 2: Maximum Security, Minimum Snacking\n\nBy the next afternoon, the Super Secure Snack Safe had stopped looking like a sturdy metal box and started looking like a nervous octopus made of locks.\n\nWires stuck out of the sides.\n\nTiny bells hung from the top.\n\nA bicycle horn was bolted to the front.\n\nSomeone had attached two flashing lights, a walnut-shaped keypad, and a sign that read:\n\n**WARNING: THIS SAFE IS EXTREMELY SERIOUS**\n\nNobody knew who wrote the sign.\n\nPapa knew.\n\nHe was very proud of it.\n\nNutty stood beside the safe wearing a tool belt, a cape, and an expression of wild scientific confidence.\n\n\"Today's installation list,\" he said, flipping through his notebook, \"includes the Tail-Print Recognition System, the Crumb-Level Alert Gauge, the Emergency Trumpet, the Flour Burst Fingerprint Cannon, and the Laser Grid.\"\n\nTony blinked. \"You have actual lasers?\"\n\n\"No,\" said Nutty. \"We have spaghetti.\"\n\nThat was somehow worse.\n\nMama had spent the morning stretching uncooked noodles across the workshop doorway in neat glowing lines. Little jars of fireflies hung behind them to make them sparkle.\n\n\"Beautiful, right?\" Mama said.\n\n\"Beautiful and deeply concerning,\" said Tony.\n\nMrs. Hedgehog adjusted her spectacles. \"What happens if someone touches a noodle?\"\n\nNutty pointed to a complicated lever system involving a bell, a whistle, a spring, and a bucket.\n\n\"We find out immediately.\"\n\nPapa was busy loading the safe with its first official contents: two cracker boxes, a jar of cinnamon acorns, one emergency cookie roll, one extra emergency cookie roll, and one secret snack sandwich \"for morale.\"\n\n\"There,\" Papa said, patting the shelf inside. \"Safe, tidy, and protected.\"\n\nNutty spun the dial. \"Time for the first test!\"\n\nThe whole town leaned in.\n\n\"Authorized user name?\" asked Nutty.\n\n\"Papa Nutwobble,\" Papa said grandly.\n\n\"Tail on scanner.\"\n\nPapa pressed his tail against the ink pad and then slapped it onto the brass plate.\n\nThe safe made a tiny clicking noise.\n\nThen another.\n\nThen the speaking tube crackled and shouted in a loud, dramatic voice:\n\n\"TAIL TOO FLUFFY. ACCESS DENIED.\"\n\nEveryone jumped.\n\nPapa stared at the safe. \"What?\"\n\n\"Impossible,\" Nutty said. \"You have the correct tail.\"\n\n\"Of course I have the correct tail.\"\n\nMama squinted at the scanner. \"Maybe it wants a flatter tail?\"\n\n\"I don't HAVE a flatter tail!\" Papa cried. \"This is my only tail!\"\n\nNutty frowned. \"Maybe the fluff setting is too strict.\"\n\nHe turned a little brass screw labeled **FUFFINESS**.\n\n\"That's spelled wrong,\" Mrs. Hedgehog said.\n\n\"Not important,\" Nutty replied.\n\n\"Spelling is always important.\"\n\n\"Later!\"\n\nThey tried again.\n\nThis time the safe accepted Papa's tail, but rejected his password.\n\n\"Please enter the secret code,\" the safe boomed.\n\nPapa cleared his throat. \"Acorn.\"\n\n\"PASSWORD TOO EASY. ACCESS DENIED.\"\n\n\"Fine. SuperAcorn.\"\n\n\"PASSWORD INSUFFICIENTLY DRAMATIC.\"\n\nPapa's whiskers trembled. \"UltraMegaCaptainCrunchyAcornDeluxe?\"\n\n\"BETTER,\" said the safe, \"BUT STILL A LITTLE EMBARRASSING.\"\n\nMayor Buttersworth nodded. \"The machine has a point.\"\n\n\"And if it can judge passwords this fiercely,\" he added, \"perhaps one day it can guard Nutville's winter acorn fund.\"\n\nMrs. Hedgehog made a note on her clipboard. \"Let us first see whether it can guard one cracker without humiliating the owner.\"\n\nPapa took a deep breath and shouted, \"SUPREME EMERGENCY SNACK COMMANDER ALPHA CRUNCH!\"\n\nThe safe paused.\n\nThen the bells rang, the lights flashed, and the horn blasted directly into Tony's ear.\n\n\"AUTHORIZED!\" the safe announced.\n\nThe crowd cheered.\n\nPapa reached for the handle.\n\nThat was when he accidentally brushed one strand of spaghetti.\n\nEverything happened at once.\n\nThe horn honked.\n\nThe bells clanged.\n\nThe flour cannon exploded.\n\nA hidden trapdoor dropped open under the welcome mat.\n\nConfetti blasted from the top.\n\nAnd the emergency trumpet played one long heroic note so loud that three cows across the river all sneezed in perfect harmony.\n\nPapa disappeared in a puff of flour and landed bottom-first in a hay basket Nutty had labeled **INTRUDER CATCH ZONE**.\n\nFor one full second, nobody moved.\n\nThen the speaking tube shouted, \"INTRUDER DETAINED. NICE TRY, CRUMB-FINGERS.\"\n\nMama fell over laughing.\n\nTony sat down in the sawdust because his legs had stopped believing in him.\n\nMrs. Hedgehog calmly wrote something on her clipboard.\n\n\"What are you writing?\" Nutty asked.\n\n\"Under 'observations,'\" she replied, \"'safe is slightly too excited.'\"\n\nPapa rose from the hay basket with confetti in his eyebrows.\n\n\"I was AUTHORIZED!\"\n\n\"Technically,\" Nutty admitted, \"you were authorized and then immediately suspicious.\"\n\n\"How?\"\n\n\"You touched the pasta lasers.\"\n\n\"Because they're in front of the HANDLE!\"\n\nNutty considered this.\n\n\"That,\" he said, \"is excellent feedback.\"\n\nFor the rest of the afternoon they made improvements.\n\nNutty moved the spaghetti.\n\nMama added faster lock wheels \"for efficiency.\"\n\nTony installed a softer horn, which was still very much a horn.\n\nMrs. Hedgehog insisted on labels for every lever.\n\nPapa suggested a snack peephole \"just so the snacks know I'm still thinking about them.\"\n\nNobody approved the peephole.\n\nPapa cleared his throat. \"Then perhaps a small bedtime standby mode? Nothing dramatic. Just something helpful in case of overnight cracker feelings.\"\n\nNutty made the face of an inventor pretending he had not heard a terrible idea.\n\nBy evening, the safe had become even more impressive and much more confusing.\n\nNutty finally locked the door with a dramatic spin of the dial.\n\n\"At last,\" he said, \"the snacks are secure.\"\n\nPapa folded his paws proudly. \"Nothing gets in.\"\n\nGrandma, who had been watching from a rocking chair with the patient expression of someone waiting for a roof to collapse, raised an eyebrow.\n\n\"Nothing gets out either,\" she observed.\n\nPapa's smile vanished.\n\n\"What do you mean?\"\n\nGrandma pointed to the front of the safe.\n\nThe new label Mrs. Hedgehog had attached read:\n\n**TO OPEN SAFE, COMPLETE ALL SEVENTEEN SECURITY STEPS IN ORDER**\n\nPapa gulped.\n\n\"How many crackers do you think are worth seventeen steps?\" Tony asked.\n\nPapa looked at the door.\n\nHe looked at the crackers inside.\n\nHe looked back at the seventeen-step list.\n\n\"...probably two,\" he said quietly.\n\nThat night he slept with the safe next to the bed, just in case the crackers needed emotional support.\n","narration":null},{"id":3,"number":3,"title":"Passwords, Panic, and Pasta Lasers","file":"chapter-3.md","markdown":"# Chapter 3: Passwords, Panic, and Pasta Lasers\n\nThe next morning, Papa wanted one cracker.\n\nJust one.\n\nNot a whole snack.\n\nNot an emergency ration.\n\nJust one small crunchy friend to go with his tea.\n\nTwenty-three minutes later, he was still on Security Step Nine.\n\n\"State your purpose,\" boomed the safe.\n\n\"I would like a cracker,\" Papa said through clenched teeth.\n\n\"STATE YOUR PURPOSE WITH MORE CONFIDENCE.\"\n\nPapa puffed up his chest. \"I WOULD LIKE A CRACKER!\"\n\n\"SUSPICIOUSLY LOUD. PROCEED TO SECURITY QUESTION.\"\n\nThe whole family gathered around.\n\n\"Security question one,\" said the safe. \"Name your first imaginary squirrel.\"\n\nPapa blinked. \"What?\"\n\nNutty flipped through his notes. \"Ah. Anti-robot test.\"\n\n\"Why would a robot want my crackers?\"\n\n\"Papa, please focus.\"\n\nPapa groaned. \"Captain Nibbles.\"\n\n\"Accepted,\" said the safe. \"Security question two. Are you now or have you ever been a goose?\"\n\n\"NO!\"\n\n\"Please answer in complete sentence.\"\n\nPapa shut his eyes. \"I have never been a goose.\"\n\n\"Good,\" said the safe. \"Geese know what they did.\"\n\nTony, who had stopped by with the morning mail, slowly backed toward the door. \"I don't think your safe is normal.\"\n\n\"Normal is how thieves win,\" Nutty replied.\n\nFinally, after another password, two tail scans, one walnut dial spin, and a suspiciously musical sneeze test, the safe clicked open.\n\nPapa reached inside with tears of relief in his eyes.\n\nThen the safe snapped shut again.\n\n\"CRACKER REMOVAL TOO GREEDY,\" it said.\n\nPapa looked down at his paw.\n\nHe was holding three crackers.\n\n\"I got excited!\"\n\nBy noon, the safe had created seventeen separate small disasters.\n\nMrs. Hedgehog stopped by to borrow cinnamon for muffins and triggered the flour cannon so hard she emerged looking like an angry powdered donut.\n\nMayor Buttersworth forgot the password halfway through saying it and got trapped in the Spaghetti Verification Corridor for eleven minutes.\n\nTony tried to deliver a parcel and was interrogated by the horn.\n\n\"Package contents?\" blared the safe.\n\n\"Socks,\" Tony answered.\n\n\"TOO VAGUE.\"\n\n\"Blue socks!\"\n\n\"STILL SHADY.\"\n\nMama was the only one who almost enjoyed it.\n\n\"I like the challenge,\" she said, crab-walking through the spaghetti beams with a muffin in her mouth.\n\n\"You set off seven alarms on purpose,\" Nutty told her.\n\n\"Because they sound neat together.\"\n\nAnd worst of all, despite all the locks and horns and flour and pasta lasers, the snacks kept disappearing.\n\nEvery morning Papa unlocked the safe using the now-ridiculous password:\n\n`SUPREME-EMERGENCY-SNACK-COMMANDER-ALPHA-CRUNCH-DELUXE-PRO-MAX`\n\nAnd every morning something was missing.\n\nOne day it was the pretzel twists.\n\nThe next day it was half the cinnamon acorns.\n\nOn Thursday, an entire emergency cookie roll vanished, leaving behind nothing but three crumbs and what looked like a very sleepy smudge.\n\nPapa clutched the safe with both paws. \"This is impossible.\"\n\nNutty nodded grimly. \"Agreed. The safe is too secure for ordinary theft.\"\n\n\"Which means,\" Mama said, leaning forward, \"we are dealing with an EXTRA-ordinary thief.\"\n\nPapa gasped. \"A master criminal.\"\n\nTony lowered his voice. \"A phantom snack bandit.\"\n\nMayor Buttersworth put on sunglasses indoors. \"A criminal genius.\"\n\nGrandma, who was eating peanuts in the corner, said, \"Or one of you is still being silly.\"\n\nNobody listened because the mystery had become too exciting.\n\nNutty pulled down the workshop map of Nutville and pinned a large note to the middle:\n\n**THE CASE OF THE IMPOSSIBLE SNACK BANDIT**\n\nHe listed the clues:\n\n- No broken locks\n- No bent hinges\n- No forced entry\n- Crumbs inside safe\n- Sleepy smudge on shelf\n- Papa becoming strangely hungry at breakfast\n- Blue fuzz on the latch\n- A delivery slip under the workbench\n- Cocoa pawprints near the rafters\n\nPapa lifted a paw. \"That last clue feels personal.\"\n\nNutty circled it anyway.\n\n\"Hold on,\" said Tony. \"Why is there a delivery slip on the suspect board?\"\n\n\"Because it says you were here at six-oh-three yesterday morning,\" Nutty replied.\n\nTony threw up his paws. \"I was delivering investigation muffins. Papa ordered them labeled `for morale.`\"\n\nMayor Buttersworth peered at the board. \"And why is there blue fuzz?\"\n\nEveryone looked at his sash.\n\n\"This is ceremonial blue,\" the mayor said quickly. \"Completely different from suspicious blue.\"\n\nMama lifted both paws. Cocoa dust puffed into the air.\n\n\"And before anyone asks,\" she said, \"yes, I did run along the rafters this morning. The lasers looked lonely.\"\n\nMrs. Hedgehog wrote on her clipboard for a long moment.\n\n\"Conclusion?\" Nutty asked.\n\n\"Annoyingly,\" she said, \"all of you remain excellent suspects.\"\n\nFor the next hour Nutty conducted official interviews.\n\nTony admitted he had come by at dawn three times that week with deliveries and once with muffins.\n\nMayor Buttersworth admitted he had tried the dial \"only a little\" because he wanted to know whether the future acorn bank would feel official enough.\n\nMama admitted she had deliberately set off two alarms and \"possibly one decorative whistle\" while testing the spaghetti beams.\n\nEach explanation made sense.\n\nEach explanation also sounded terrible.\n\nThe mystery grew boots and started tap-dancing.\n\nBy sunset, the investigation was in full swing.\n\nMama dusted the floor with cocoa powder to catch footprints.\n\nTony hid behind a barrel wearing a fake mustache for detective reasons.\n\nMrs. Hedgehog set up a clue table with labeled jars.\n\nMayor Buttersworth insisted on a code name and chose `Eagle Seven`, even though he was not an eagle and there was no `Eagle One` through `Eagle Six`.\n\nPapa sat in a chair by the safe holding a flashlight, a notebook, and a sandwich he had promised not to eat unless things got \"investigatively intense.\"\n\nAt exactly midnight, everybody froze.\n\nThe workshop was quiet.\n\nThe safe sat gleaming in the moonlight.\n\nThe cocoa powder remained smooth.\n\nThe bells were still.\n\nThe spaghetti lasers glowed softly.\n\nThen, from the far corner of the room, came a sound.\n\nNot a footstep.\n\nNot a creak.\n\nNot a whisper.\n\nA snore.\n\nEveryone slowly turned.\n\nPapa was asleep in his chair.\n\nHis chin had dropped to his chest.\n\nHis paws were folded over his sandwich.\n\nAnd in his sleep, very softly but very clearly, he mumbled:\n\n\"Emergency... crunchy support...\"\n\nThe safe lit up.\n\nIts lights flashed.\n\nIts dial spun by itself.\n\nAnd the speaking tube said, in a strangely cheerful tone:\n\n\"MIDNIGHT COMFORT SNACK PROTOCOL ACTIVATED.\"\n\nNutty's eyes bulged.\n\n\"I did not know it HAD a midnight comfort snack protocol.\"\n\nThen the safe door flew open.\n\nAnd the snack conveyor started moving.\n","narration":null},{"id":4,"number":4,"title":"The Midnight Cruncher","file":"chapter-4.md","markdown":"# Chapter 4: The Midnight Cruncher\n\nNobody had known there was a snack conveyor inside the safe.\n\nIncluding Nutty.\n\nEspecially Nutty.\n\n\"Why is there a conveyor belt?\" Tony whispered.\n\n\"Because Papa kept asking for a snack elevator,\" Nutty whispered back. \"I told him no. I may have accidentally built a sideways one.\"\n\nPapa snored again.\n\n\"Crunchy support...\" he mumbled.\n\nThe safe hummed with mechanical delight.\n\nOne by one, crackers, pretzel twists, and cinnamon acorns rolled onto the conveyor and slid neatly into Papa's lap.\n\nHe did not wake up.\n\nHe simply accepted the snacks in his sleep with the calm experience of a squirrel who had apparently trained for this his entire life.\n\nThe workshop was silent for one beat.\n\nThen Papa shifted in the chair, mumbled, \"Need backup cookie,\" and the safe answered:\n\n\"DOUBLE COMFORT MODE ENGAGED.\"\n\nThe conveyor belt sped up.\n\n\"Oh no,\" said Nutty.\n\n\"Oh YES,\" said the safe.\n\nThree cookie rolls shot out like cannonballs.\n\nMama caught one.\n\nTony caught one.\n\nMayor Buttersworth did not catch one.\n\nIt bounced off his sash and landed in the clue table, which collapsed into a cloud of labeled flour jars.\n\nMrs. Hedgehog adjusted her dusty glasses. \"Well. That explains the missing snacks.\"\n\nPapa, still asleep, now had a tower of crackers in his lap and a cinnamon acorn balanced on his head.\n\nNutty stared in disbelief. \"The safe thinks Papa is an authorized nighttime emergency.\"\n\nGrandma crunched another peanut. \"Because he is.\"\n\nPapa snored louder.\n\nThe safe horn gave a tiny toot of admiration.\n\nThen Papa did the worst possible thing.\n\nHe smiled in his sleep and whispered, \"Maximum snacks.\"\n\nThe safe went wild.\n\n\"MASTER COMMAND CONFIRMED!\" it shouted.\n\nEvery lock popped.\n\nThe warning lights spun.\n\nThe bells clanged.\n\nThe flour cannon fired.\n\nThe confetti launcher exploded.\n\nThe emergency trumpet blared a note so heroic that it sounded like a parade had fallen down the stairs.\n\nAnd the conveyor belt began flinging snacks in every direction.\n\nCrackers flew across the workshop like tiny crunchy frisbees.\n\nPretzels rained from the rafters.\n\nA whole shower of cinnamon acorns poured through the speaking tube and bounced off the floor like spicy little marbles.\n\n\"TAKE COVER!\" yelled Mama, diving behind a barrel.\n\n\"THIS IS ALREADY COVERED IN FLOUR!\" yelled Tony from under the clue table.\n\nMayor Buttersworth tried to command the situation and was immediately hit in the forehead by a very enthusiastic cheese cracker.\n\nOutside, lights flicked on all over Nutville.\n\nMrs. Rabbit opened her window just in time to catch a pretzel in her teacup.\n\nMr. Mole looked up from his tunnel and said, \"If this is another innovation, I object.\"\n\nThree raccoons in the square looked around in amazement as cookies began falling from the sky.\n\nInside the workshop, Nutty lunged for the emergency lever.\n\nThe lever snapped off in his paw.\n\n\"That feels bad,\" he said.\n\n\"Try the shutdown switch!\" cried Mama.\n\n\"There are six shutdown switches!\"\n\n\"WHY?\"\n\n\"REDUNDANCY!\"\n\nPapa stood up.\n\nStill asleep.\n\nStill holding a sandwich.\n\nStill being pelted by his own snacks.\n\nHe began sleepwalking toward the safe in slow, determined steps.\n\nThe spaghetti lasers glowed.\n\nEveryone held their breath.\n\nPapa walked straight through them.\n\nNothing happened.\n\nNutty slapped both paws to his forehead. \"I left the family setting on!\"\n\n\"There is a family setting?\" Tony shouted.\n\n\"Of course!\"\n\n\"What does it do?\"\n\n\"Mostly betrayal!\"\n\nPapa reached the open safe, hugged it gently, and said, \"You understand me.\"\n\nThe safe answered in a warm, proud voice, \"YOU ARE WELCOME, SUPREME COMMANDER.\"\n\nGrandma stood up at last.\n\nShe dusted peanut skins from her apron.\n\nShe watched the flying crackers.\n\nShe watched Nutty crawling under flashing wires.\n\nShe watched Mama wrestling the trumpet.\n\nShe watched Tony get stuck in the spaghetti.\n\nThen she sighed and said, \"Children, move.\"\n\nEverybody moved.\n\nGrandma stepped calmly through the chaos and reached into her apron.\n\nOut came the tiny stick of dynamite from the first day.\n\nNutty made a strangled squeak. \"Grandma.\"\n\n\"Relax,\" Grandma said. \"This is a polite amount.\"\n\nShe lit the fuse with a match, set the tiny stick beside a jammed panel on the back of the safe, and stepped away.\n\nThere was a small, tidy:\n\n**POOF!**\n\nA puff of soot rose into the air.\n\nThe jammed panel popped loose and landed neatly at Tony's feet.\n\nGrandma nodded once, satisfied, and reached behind the safe.\n\nThere she found a small metal panel labeled:\n\n**DO NOT PUT KEY HERE**\n\nStuck under the panel, with a bit of tape, was the plain iron key she had given them on the first day.\n\nThe workshop went still.\n\nNutty's jaw fell open. \"I told everyone not to put the key there.\"\n\nGrandma held up the key. \"And naturally one of you did exactly that.\"\n\nShe unlocked a tiny hidden slot.\n\nInside was a second lever.\n\nThis one was labeled:\n\n**REALLY ACTUALLY STOP EVERYTHING**\n\nGrandma pulled it.\n\nThe bells stopped.\n\nThe horn died.\n\nThe lights dimmed.\n\nThe conveyor belt slowed.\n\nOne final lonely pretzel popped out, hit Papa on the nose, and bounced into Grandma's teacup.\n\nPapa snored once more, sat back down in the chair, and kept chewing peacefully in his sleep.\n\nThe whole workshop stared at Grandma.\n\nShe sipped her pretzel tea and shrugged.\n\n\"I did mention the plain key.\"\n","narration":null},{"id":5,"number":5,"title":"Grandma Opens Everything","file":"chapter-5.md","markdown":"# Chapter 5: Grandma Opens Everything\n\nThe next morning, Nutville looked like a party hosted by crackers.\n\nThe town square had pretzels in the fountain.\n\nThe mayor's statue wore a cookie around its neck.\n\nMrs. Rabbit found cinnamon acorns in her rain boots.\n\nMr. Mole charged two peanuts to remove \"unauthorized snack rubble\" from his tunnel entrance.\n\nPapa woke up in the workshop chair with a cracker on his shoulder, flour in his fur, and no memory of anything after about sunset.\n\n\"Why am I wearing the trumpet?\" he asked.\n\nBecause he was.\n\nIt was around his neck like a very confused necklace.\n\nNutty placed the evidence table in front of him.\n\nOn it sat:\n\n- The empty safe\n- The taped-over secret key slot\n- A logbook from the safe\n- Sixteen pretzels\n- One note that read `MIDNIGHT COMFORT SNACK PROTOCOL ACTIVATED`\n\nPapa read the note twice.\n\nThen he looked up slowly.\n\n\"I would like to state for the record,\" he said, \"that Sleepy Papa and Awake Papa have very different ideas about discipline.\"\n\nMama burst out laughing so hard she slid out of her chair.\n\nTony wiped tears from his eyes. \"You built a machine that obeys your dreams.\"\n\nNutty flipped open the logbook.\n\n\"Worse,\" he said. \"I accidentally trained the voice box on Papa while he was muttering about crackers.\"\n\nHe turned the pages toward the others.\n\n\"And then I connected the family setting, the conveyor belt, the voice box, and...\" He squinted. \"Oh no. The bedtime standby notes.\"\n\n\"The what notes?\" Tony asked.\n\nNutty read aloud:\n\n- `snack elevator?`\n- `morale sandwich shelf`\n- `family override`\n- `tiny overnight cracker help for Papa maybe`\n\nMama clapped both paws over her mouth.\n\n\"I thought I was ignoring that last suggestion,\" Nutty said. \"Apparently I was engineering it.\"\n\nPapa studied the list and winced.\n\n\"In fairness,\" he said, \"I may have requested several convenience features while hungry.\"\n\n\"Several?\" said Mama.\n\n\"A modest number,\" Papa replied. \"Somewhere between three and eleven.\"\n\n\"You asked for an overnight cracker setting?\" Tony said.\n\nPapa looked offended. \"A tiny one. For emergencies. I did not ask it to achieve sentience and fire pretzels at the mayor.\"\n\nGrandma tapped the safe. \"And your seventeen security steps did exactly what overcomplicated security always does.\"\n\n\"What's that?\" Nutty asked.\n\n\"It made the machine so busy protecting the snacks from everyone else that it forgot to protect the town from itself.\"\n\nNutty stared at the floorboards.\n\nHe hated it when Grandma was exactly right because she was always exactly right in such a calm voice.\n\n\"So what do we do now?\" Papa asked. \"I still want my snacks safe.\"\n\nGrandma reached into her bag and set a plain wooden box on the table.\n\nIt had one sturdy lid.\n\nOne lock.\n\nAnd one key.\n\nThat was all.\n\n\"This,\" she said, \"is a snack box.\"\n\nEveryone looked at it.\n\n\"That's it?\" said Nutty.\n\n\"That's it.\"\n\n\"No horn?\" Mama asked.\n\n\"No horn.\"\n\n\"No flour cannon?\" Tony asked hopefully.\n\n\"No flour cannon.\"\n\n\"No goose question?\" said Papa.\n\n\"Absolutely no goose question.\"\n\nPapa considered the box with deep suspicion. \"How will it know I am important?\"\n\nGrandma patted his shoulder. \"It won't. That is part of its charm.\"\n\nFor one long second, nobody said anything.\n\nThen Nutty started to laugh.\n\nNot a tiny laugh.\n\nA real laugh.\n\nThe kind that begins in your belly and bounces out before pride can stop it.\n\n\"We built a snack safe so secure it launched pretzels at the mayor,\" he said.\n\nMama snorted. \"And interrogated Tony about socks.\"\n\n\"And called me crumb-fingers,\" Papa said, offended all over again.\n\nSoon the whole workshop was roaring with laughter.\n\nEven Mrs. Hedgehog smiled, though only with the left side of her face because that was apparently how she did wild joy.\n\nNutty wiped his eyes. \"So the good news is, we did build a machine that can guard something.\"\n\n\"The bad news,\" said Papa, \"is that the something cannot be snacks if I am asleep within shouting distance.\"\n\nBy afternoon, the Super Secure Snack Safe had a new job.\n\nMayor Buttersworth clasped his paws together. \"At last! A place for Nutville's winter acorn fund that is not my desk drawer.\"\n\n\"Or your teapot,\" Mrs. Hedgehog said.\n\n\"Or your sash pocket,\" Tony added.\n\n\"We do not need the full list,\" said the mayor quickly.\n\nThey rolled it to the town square, polished off the flour, and painted new words on the front:\n\n**NUTVILLE'S SUPER SECURE ACORN BANK**\n\nThe speaking tube still worked, so Nutty re-tuned the voice box.\n\nNow, whenever someone dropped in a savings acorn, a rainy-day acorn, or a whole jar for the winter-help fund, the safe cheerfully announced:\n\n\"ACORN SAFELY BANKED. NO EXPLOSION DETECTED.\"\n\nThe town loved it.\n\nMrs. Hedgehog kept the ledger.\n\nMayor Buttersworth practiced saying \"municipal acorn reserves\" in a very deep official voice.\n\nPapa loved the new snack box too, although he tried very hard not to show it.\n\nIt opened quickly.\n\nIt closed quietly.\n\nAnd best of all, it did not throw crackers at anybody.\n\nAt dinner that night, he locked away a fresh batch of emergency cookies and slipped the key into his vest pocket.\n\n\"Simple,\" he said with a proud nod. \"Elegant. Reliable.\"\n\nGrandma sipped her tea.\n\n\"Where's the key now?\" she asked.\n\nPapa froze.\n\nHe checked his vest.\n\nHe checked his other vest.\n\nHe checked under his plate, inside the bread basket, behind his ear, and somehow in Mama's flower pot.\n\n\"...interesting,\" he said faintly.\n\nNutty leaned back in his chair, grinning.\n\n\"Should I design a key-finding machine?\"\n\nEveryone shouted, \"NO!\"\n\nThen, from the pocket of Papa's trumpet necklace hanging by the door, came a tiny metallic clink.\n\nThe key.\n\nGrandma closed her eyes.\n\n\"I am surrounded by professionals,\" she said.\n\nPapa retrieved it, locked the snack box again, and patted the lid lovingly.\n\n\"This time,\" he said, \"nothing can possibly go wrong.\"\n\nFrom the town square outside, the repurposed safe cheerfully boomed:\n\n\"THIS IS AN ACORN BANK. TURNIP REJECTED.\"\n\nNutty's ears perked up.\n\nMama grinned.\n\nTony shouted from the road, \"Who tried to bank a turnip?\"\n\nPapa looked at the trumpet necklace.\n\nHe looked at the snack box.\n\nHe looked at his family.\n\nThen he sighed the sigh of a squirrel who knew peace would never last more than about six minutes in Nutville.\n\n\"Fine,\" he said, standing up. \"But this time we are absolutely, definitely, one hundred percent not adding lasers.\"\n\nNutty quietly closed his notebook over a sketch labeled **Turnip Security Improvements**.\n\nFor now.\n\n**THE END**\n","narration":null}],"chapterCount":5,"audio":null,"narration":{"hasNarration":false,"chapters":[]},"assets":[],"standalone":false};
